<bibRefCitation author="Lester RN &amp; Hazan SMZ" box="[425,453,1078,1100]" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="521 - 523" part="39" refId="ref11326" refString="40. Lester RN, Hazan SMZ (1990) The distinction between Solanum incanum L. and Solanum insanum L. Taxon 39: 521 - 523." title="The distinction between Solanum incanum L. and Solanum insanum L" type="journal article" year="1990">40</bibRefCitation>
] and one-way pre-zygotic barriers have been suggested as the reason for this failure of fruit set in crosses with 
<taxonomicName box="[281,376,1134,1156]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[281,376,1134,1156]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[431,557,1134,1156]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lichtensteinii">
<emphasis box="[431,557,1134,1156]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. lichtensteinii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<bibRefCitation author="Samuels J" box="[574,602,1134,1156]" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bull" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 11" part="67" refId="ref11037" refString="31. Samuels J (2012) Solanum incanum s. l. (Solanaceae): taxonomic relationships between S. incanum, S. campylacanthum, S. panduriforme and S. lichtensteinii. Kew Bull 67: 1 - 11." title="Solanum incanum s. l. (Solanaceae): taxonomic relationships between S. incanum, S. campylacanthum, S. panduriforme and S. lichtensteinii" type="journal article" year="2012">31</bibRefCitation>
]. It is possible that some of these difficulties could be due to ploidy differences within 
<taxonomicName box="[155,316,1190,1212]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="campylacanthum">
<emphasis box="[155,316,1190,1212]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. campylacanthum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Anaso and Uzo [41,42] reported tetraploidy in 
<taxonomicName box="[155,315,1218,1240]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="campylacanthum">
<emphasis box="[155,315,1218,1240]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. campylacanthum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Nigeria (reported as 
<taxonomicName box="[577,670,1218,1240]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[577,670,1218,1240]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); their study illustrates the problems with inconsistent application of names in this group, they compared wild tetraploid ‘‘S. incanum’’ (= 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="campylacanthum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. campylacanthum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) with cultivated diploid ‘‘S. incanum’’ (= 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aethiopicum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. aethiopicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., the unrelated scarlet eggplant). Fortunately they illustrated the plants used in the studies and identification of their material is clear even in the absence of vouchers. There has been an assumption that all relatives are, like the eggplant itself, diploid and earlier cytogenetic studies have not explicitly cited vouchers for counts of ‘‘S. incanum’’ so verification of identities of taxa counted is difficult. Ploidy level variation in 
<taxonomicName box="[633,704,1497,1518]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[633,704,1497,1518]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Solanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most common in the potatoes, where the cultivated potato has a number of ploidy forms and wild species vary from diploid to hexaploid [
<bibRefCitation author="Simon R &amp; Xie CH &amp; Clausen A &amp; Jansky S &amp; Halterman D" box="[266,294,1581,1603]" journalOrPublisher="Invasive Pl Sci Managem" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="286 - 293" part="3" refId="ref10324" refString="12. Simon R, Xie CH, Clausen A, Jansky S, Halterman D, et al. (2010) Wild and cultivated potato (Solanum sect. Petota) escaped and persistent outside of its natural range. Invasive Pl Sci Managem 3: 286 - 293." title="Wild and cultivated potato (Solanum sect. Petota) escaped and persistent outside of its natural range" type="journal article" year="2010">12</bibRefCitation>
], and in the Morelloid clade (
<taxonomicName authority="L." authorityName="L." box="[601,716,1581,1603]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nigrum">
<emphasis box="[601,685,1581,1602]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. nigrum</emphasis>
L.
</taxonomicName>
and its relatives; see [
<bibRefCitation author="Manoko MLK" box="[301,329,1609,1631]" journalOrPublisher="Radboud University, Nijmegen, The Netherlands" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" refId="ref11405" refString="43. Manoko MLK (2007) A systematic study of African Solanum L. section Solanum (Solanaceae). PhD thesis, Radboud University, Nijmegen, The Netherlands." title="A systematic study of African Solanum L. section Solanum (Solanaceae)" type="book" year="2007">43</bibRefCitation>
]), but it also occurs in some species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bitter" authorityYear="1921" baseAuthorityName="Dunal" box="[155,312,1637,1659]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Leptostemonum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Leptostemonum</taxonomicName>
clade, particularly in widespread weedy species such as 
<taxonomicName authority="Cav." authorityName="Cav." box="[233,428,1665,1687]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="elaeagnifolium">
<emphasis box="[233,374,1665,1686]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. elaeagnifolium</emphasis>
Cav.
</taxonomicName>
[
<bibRefCitation author="Scaldaferro M &amp; Chiarini F &amp; Santinaque JF &amp; Bernadello G &amp; Moscone E" box="[442,472,1665,1687]" journalOrPublisher="Genet Resour Crop Evol" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="1833 - 1847" part="69" refId="ref11437" refString="44. Scaldaferro M, Chiarini F, Santinaque JF, Bernadello G, Moscone E (2012) Geographical pattern and ploidy levels of the weed Solanum elaeagnifolium (Solanaceae) in Argentina. Genet Resour Crop Evol 69: 1833 - 1847." title="Geographical pattern and ploidy levels of the weed Solanum elaeagnifolium (Solanaceae) in Argentina" type="journal article" year="2012">44</bibRefCitation>
].
</paragraph>
